0C0647</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The details of the pathways and surface enzymology of polyglucan biosynthesis in plants and microbes are surprisingly poorly understood despite their importance in biology and industry. The approach of our multidisciplinary research is the study of the enzymes that are involved in these systems using biochemical and biophysical techniques along with synthetic chemistry and complementary molecular biology studies addressing their physiological functions. Specifically, we are studying developmentally regulated glycogen metabolism in Streptomyces coelicolor, surface enzymology of relevance to the developing starch granule in plants and bacterial exopolysaccharide biosynthesis (e.g. dextran). These systems relate to antimicrobial agents and the engineering of novel starches and glucans.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2017-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_PROJECTED</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1185488</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Our findings have been used by MRC Technology to try to find novel therapies against tuberculosis.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>1DDBA8DA-B284-47C1-9A00-ABE1E78376AF</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>545cf799e94606.82835554</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have developed and employed a number of tools to better understand the role of carbohydrates in microbes and plants. We have used a combination of chemistry and structural biology to understand how enzymes such as GlgE catalyse key steps in metabolism relevant to Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Thus, we have completely redrawn the metabolic map for alpha-glucan biosynthesis in a major pathogen and identified new potential drug targets. We have used spectroscopy and genetics to understand how other enzyme of the GlgE pathway, such as trehalose synthase, operate in vivo. We have also understood the substrate specificity and allosteric regulation of other enzymes of related pathways. We have used ion mobility mass spectrometry to discriminate between different glucose polymers, something only done with much smaller molecules to date. We have used computational biology to discover how widespread the GlgE pathway is among bacteria. We have identified how Streptomyces species metabolise alpha-glucans. We have also developed surface-based methods to allow a better evaluation of enzymes that operate on surfaces such as that of the starch granule in plants.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The tools that we have developed will be applicable to a wide range of biological systems by us and others. These include other pathogens other than Mycobacterium. We have provided the fundamental understanding of a new potential drug target in Mycobacterium tuberculosis. This may lead to novel therapies in the long term.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>F7E44E40-6EEA-45A0-B7CB-B54B0DB171A0</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>545f7dd3c45967.39039587</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Healthcare,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOu